{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"20ccc797-3e82-430e-a81b-4005a6d18bce","content":"There's no project at that path yet. Here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"Microsoft.NET.Sdk\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n    <!-- Makes this a dotnet tool -->\n    <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n    <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n    <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n    <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n    <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n    <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n    <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n    <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n- **`PackAsTool`** — required; marks the project as a global/local dotnet tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name users invoke (defaults to assembly name).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n**Publishing steps:**\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to create or update an existing `.csproj` file with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd4fe075-eea4-4ead-a8a5-29441acae71b","outputTokens":506},"id":"e739f2dc-caa4-4a2a-aea9-6d84cb4b71a1","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:49.249Z","parentId":"1237a353-95ce-4bac-a408-ec112a3ba482"}
